<paragraph blockId="15.[136,1452,736,1447]" box="[136,513,736,763]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">
31. 
<taxonomicName authority="Barneby" authorityName="Barneby" box="[178,513,736,763]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,410,736,763]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Mimosa orbignyana</emphasis>
Barneby
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="216" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[136,1452,736,1447]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">
This species has remained poorly understood, known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[873,921,773,799]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">type</typeStatus>
collection (
<emphasis box="[1050,1213,772,799]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">díOrbigny 743</emphasis>
P, 
<collectingCountry box="[1241,1326,773,799]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, Chiquitos, 
<date box="[136,284,809,835]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" value="1831-08">August 1831</date>
), and apparently never re-collected since, until very recently. It was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Barneby, R. C." box="[1205,1381,809,835]" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" pagination="1 - 835" part="65" refString="Barneby, R. C. (1991) Sensitivae Censitae: a description of the genus Mimosa L. (Mimosaceae) in the New World. Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 65: 1 - 835." title="Sensitivae Censitae: a description of the genus Mimosa L. (Mimosaceae) in the New World" type="journal article" year="1991">Barneby (1991)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">
‘in unknown habitat, but to be sought in campo or cerrado at or above 
<quantity box="[889,958,845,871]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" unit="m" value="700.0">700 m</quantity>
on the Sierra de Santiago, near 
<geoCoordinate box="[1320,1423,845,871]" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" precision="925" value="-18.5">18° 30´S</geoCoordinate>
in south-east 
<collectingRegion box="[257,384,881,907]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
, Boliviaí
</emphasis>
and has been considered endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[893,975,881,907]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. Within the last two years, two collections, both from further north, on the Serranía Huanchaca have been made (
<emphasis box="[948,1160,916,942]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">J.R.I. Wood 26772</emphasis>
, 
<collectionCode box="[1177,1231,917,943]" country="Bolivia" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15532" name="Herbario Nacional de Bolivia, Universidad Mayor de San Andr�s" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">LPB</collectionCode>
, K, 
<collectionCode box="[1283,1339,917,943]" country="Bolivia" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15753" name="Museo de Historia Natural Noel Kempff Mercado -- Universidad Aut�noma Gabriel Ren� Moreno" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">USZ</collectionCode>
, from the southwest part of the meseta of the Serranía Huanchaca in the Noel Kempf National Park in 
<collectingCountry box="[1195,1280,953,979]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">L. Borges 787</emphasis>
, UB, from the southern end of the Huanchaca range in neighbouring 
<collectingRegion box="[973,1120,989,1015]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1159,1230,989,1015]" name="Brazil" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, where the range is known as the Serra do Ricardo Franco). However, despite extensive fieldwork in areas where d’Orbigny is likely to have visited in ‘Chiquitos’, no material matching this species has been re-collected from any of these areas. This is perhaps surprising, given that 
<taxonomicName box="[478,646,1096,1122]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis box="[478,646,1096,1122]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. orbignyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms a substantial shrub to 
<quantity box="[975,1020,1097,1123]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" unit="m" value="2.0">2 m</quantity>
height, multi-stemmed from the base, resprouting after fire from an underground woody root system that is much thicker than the above-ground stems, and with conspicuous 
<quantity box="[338,430,1169,1195]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" unit="m" value="1.1" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.0">1–1.2 m</quantity>
tall efoliate pseudoracemes of bright pink flowers (
<figureCitation box="[1008,1085,1169,1195]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="16.[136,229,2024,2046]" captionTargetBox="[234,1362,209,1978]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[189,1398,190,1997]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 6. Mimosa orbignyana. A. Habit and flowering shoots; B. Stipules; C. Leaflets; D. Floral bracts; E. Flower; F. Longitudinal section of flower, all from J. R. I. Wood et al. 26772 (LPB, K). Drawn by Rosemary Wise." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/192181/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation box="[1121,1137,1169,1195]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[136,229,949,971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,923]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,190,923]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Mimosa orbignyana. A. Habit; B. habitat; C. multiple stems from base resprouting after fire; D. leaves; E. indumentum; F. inflorescences. All from L. Borges 787 (UB), Serranía Huanchaca. Photos by Leonardo Borges." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/192182/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">7</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Barneby, R. C." box="[1158,1334,1169,1195]" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" pagination="1 - 835" part="65" refString="Barneby, R. C. (1991) Sensitivae Censitae: a description of the genus Mimosa L. (Mimosaceae) in the New World. Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 65: 1 - 835." title="Sensitivae Censitae: a description of the genus Mimosa L. (Mimosaceae) in the New World" type="journal article" year="1991">Barneby (1991)</bibRefCitation>
placed 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. orbignyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in his ser. 
<emphasis box="[386,472,1205,1231]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Setosae</emphasis>
of sect. 
<emphasis box="[566,675,1204,1230]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Habbasia</emphasis>
and indicated likely affinities to 
<emphasis box="[1045,1163,1204,1230]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. riedelii</emphasis>
Benth. from the Chapada dos Guimar„es in 
<collectingRegion box="[348,496,1241,1267]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
and 
<emphasis box="[556,700,1241,1266]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. aguapeia</emphasis>
Barneby from the Serra do Aguapei also in 
<collectingRegion box="[1220,1372,1241,1267]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
. These overall affinities are confirmed by analysis of a 
<emphasis box="[677,787,1277,1303]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">trnD -trnT</emphasis>
sequence of 
<taxonomicName box="[937,1104,1276,1302]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis box="[937,1104,1276,1302]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. orbignyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as sister to a clade comprising ser. 
<emphasis box="[180,266,1313,1339]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Setosae</emphasis>
and ser. 
<emphasis box="[362,510,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Pachycarpae</emphasis>
(clade O in 
<bibRefCitation author="Dahmer, N. &amp; Simon, M. F. &amp; Schifino-Wittmann, M. T. &amp; Hughes, C. E. &amp; Miotto, S. T. S. &amp; Giuliani, J. C." box="[644,849,1312,1339]" journalOrPublisher="Plant Systematics &amp; Evolution" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" pagination="211 - 220" part="291" publicationUrl="http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s00606-010-0382-2" refString="Dahmer, N., Simon, M. F., Schifino-Wittmann, M. T., Hughes, C. E., Miotto, S. T. S. &amp; Giuliani, J. C. (2011) Chromosome numbers in the genus Mimosa L.: cytotaxonomic and evolutionary implications. Plant Systematics &amp; Evolution 291: 211 - 220. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00606 - 010 - 0382 - 2" title="Chromosome numbers in the genus Mimosa L.: cytotaxonomic and evolutionary implications" type="journal article" year="2011">
Simon 
<emphasis box="[724,772,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">et al</emphasis>
. (2011
</bibRefCitation>
)) plus 
<emphasis box="[926,1103,1312,1338]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. corynadenia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1117,1181,1313,1339]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,198,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,190,1893]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Chloroplast phylogeny of Mimosa. A. 50 % majority-rule consensus tree based on Bayesian analysis of 382 trnD - trnT noncoding plastid sequences. Numbers above branches are posterior probability values. The major clades proposed by Simon et al. (2011) are indicated with letters and sizes are proportional to the number of accessions included. B. Detail of clades containing new species here described from Bolivia and other newly generated sequences of species of doubtful identity are highlighted in grey." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/192176/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Although no sequence data are available yet for 
<emphasis box="[433,554,1348,1374]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. riedelii</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[614,758,1349,1374]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. aguapeia</emphasis>
, the discovery of 
<taxonomicName box="[970,1139,1348,1374]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Mimosa" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="orbignyana">
<emphasis box="[970,1139,1348,1374]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">M. orbignyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Serranía Huanchaca confirms Barneby’s notion that these three potentially closely allied species occupy disjunct ranges on these ancient sandstone chapadas around the periphery of the upper Rio 
<collectingCountry box="[793,897,1421,1447]" name="Paraguay" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">
<collectingRegion box="[793,897,1421,1447]" country="Paraguay" name="Asuncion" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Paraguay</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
basin.
</paragraph>
